eveloper tools\", \"Claude Code\", \"memory management\", \"slash commands\"],\n    70→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    71→  },\n    72→  {\n    73→    \"title\": \"Interactive explanations and cognitive debt\",\n    74→    \"description\": \"Simon Willison discusses 'cognitive debt' - when we lose track of how code written by agents works. While simple code doesn't matter, when core application logic becomes a black box, it becomes harder to plan new features and slows progress like technical debt. He advocates for interactive explanations that help maintain understanding of agent-generated code.\",\n    75→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n    76→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n    77→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/guides/agentic-engineering-patterns/interactive-explanations/\",\n    78→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-28\",\n    79→    \"topics\": [\"AI\", \"LLMs\", \"coding agents\", \"AI-assisted programming\", \"cognitive debt\", \"generative AI\", \"explorables\", \"agentic engineering\"],\n    80→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    81→  },\n    82→  {\n    83→    \"title\": \"An AI agent coding skeptic tries AI agent coding\",\n    84→    \"description\": \"Max Woolf's detailed account of becoming an AI agent coding believer after testing increasingly ambitious projects. He describes porting Python's scikit-learn to Rust as 'rustlearn' using agents. Woolf notes Opus 4.6/Codex 5.3 are 'an order of magnitude better than coding LLMs released just months before it' but acknowledges difficulty communicating this without sounding like hype.\",\n    85→    \"author\": \"Max Woolf (shared by Simon Willison)\",\n    86→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n    87→    \"url\": \"https://minimaxir.com/2026/02/ai-agent-coding/\",\n    88→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-27\",\n    89→    \"topics\": [\"Python\", \"AI\", \"Rust\", \"generative AI\", \"LLMs\", \"AI-assisted programming\", \"coding agents\", \"agentic engineering\", \"November 2025 inflection\"],\n    90→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    91→  },\n    92→  {\n    93→    \"title\": \"Free Claude Max for open source maintainers\",\n    94→    \"description\": \"Anthropic is offering Claude Max 20x plan ($200/month) for free to open source maintainers for six months. Criteria: maintainers of public repos with 5,000+ GitHub stars or 1M+ monthly NPM downloads, with commits in the last 3 months. Anthropic notes they'll accept up to 10,000 contributors on a rolling basis.\",\n    95→    \"author\": \"Anthropic (shared by Simon Willison)\",\n    96→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n    97→    \"url\": \"https://claude.com/contact-sales/claude-for-oss\",\n    98→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-27\",\n    99→    \"topics\": [\"open-source\", \"AI\", \"generative AI\", \"LLMs\", \"Anthropic\", \"Claude\"],\n   100→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   101→  },\n   102→  {\n   103→    \"title\": \"Unicode Explorer using binary search over HTTP range requests\",\n   104→    \"description\": \"Simon Willison built a Unicode Explorer that uses binary search over HTTP Range requests against a 76.6MB file. The demo visualizes each step of the binary search, showing fetch times and comparisons. He learned that Range request tricks aren't compatible with HTTP compression but CDNs like Cloudflare automatically skip compression with content-range headers.\",\n   105→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n   106→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   107→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/2026/Feb/27/unicode-explorer/\",\n   108→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-27\",\n   109→    \"topics\": [\"algorithms\", \"HTTP\", \"research\", \"tools\", \"unicode\", \"AI\", \"generative AI\", \"LLMs\", \"AI-assisted programming\", \"vibe-coding\", \"HTTP range requests\"],\n   110→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   111→  },\n   112→  {\n   113→    \"title\": \"Continue v1.3.32: MCP App support and cn checks\",\n   114→    \"description\": \"Continue released v1.3.32 adding limited MCP App support, cn checks CLI command, enabled agent mode for LM Studio models, updated default model to Claude Opus 4.6, and consolidated React best practices. This release continues expanding MCP ecosystem integration.\",\n   115→    \"author\": \"Continue Dev Team\",\n   116→    \"source\": \"Product\",\n   117→    \"url\": \"https://github.com/continuedev/continue/releases\",\n   118→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-27\",\n   119→    \"topics\": [\"AI coding\", \"MCP\", \"Continue\", \"agent mode\", \"React\"],\n   120→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   121→  },\n   122→  {\n   123→    \"title\": \"Andrej Karpathy on programming transformation in December\",\n   124→    \"description\": \"Andrej Karpathy shared that programming fundamentally changed in the last 2 months, specifically December: 'coding agents basically didn't work before December and basically work since.' He notes models now have 'significantly higher quality, long-term coherence and tenacity' and can 'power through large and long tasks,' making this 'extremely disruptive to the default programming workflow.'\",\n   125→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy (quoted by Simon Willison)\",\n   126→    \"source\": \"Twitter\",\n   127→    \"url\": \"https://twitter.com/karpathy/status/2026731645169185220\",\n   128→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-26\",\n   129→    \"topics\": [\"AI\", \"Andrej Karpathy\", \"generative AI\", \"LLMs\", \"AI-assisted programming\", \"coding agents\", \"agentic engineering\", \"November 2025 inflection\"],\n   130→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   131→  },\n   132→  {\n   133→    \"title\": \"Google API Keys security vulnerability\",\n   134→    \"description\": \"Critical security issue: Google Maps and Gemini share the same API keys, but Maps keys are designed to be public (embedded in websites) while Gemini keys can access private files and make billable requests. When Gemini API is enabled on a project with existing public Maps keys, those keys gain unexpected privileges. Truffle Security found 2,863 API keys in November 2025 Common Crawl that could access Gemini.\",\n   135→    \"author\": \"Truffle Security (shared by Simon Willison)\",\n   136→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   137→    \"url\": \"https://trufflesecurity.com/blog/google-api-keys-werent-secrets-but-then-gemini-changed-the-rules\",\n   138→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-26\",\n   139→    \"topics\": [\"API keys\", \"Google\", \"security\", \"Gemini\"],\n   140→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   141→  },\n   142→  {\n   143→    \"title\": \"Cursor Bugbot Autofix with Cloud Agents\",\n   144→    \"description\": \"Cursor's Bugbot can automatically fix issues it finds in pull requests using cloud agents that run in isolated VMs with full development environments. Over 35% of autofix changes are merged into base PRs. Resolution rate increased from 52% to 76%. Community feedback highlights efficiency gains but also concerns about over-reliance and code understanding.\",\n   145→    \"author\": \"Cursor Team\",\n   146→    \"source\": \"Product\",\n   147→    \"url\": \"https://cursor.com/changelog\",\n   148→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-26\",\n   149→    \"topics\": [\"AI coding\", \"Cursor\", \"autonomous agents\", \"PR automation\", \"cloud agents\"],\n   150→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   151→  },\n   152→  {\n   153→    \"title\": \"Cursor Cloud Agents with Computer Use\",\n   154→    \"description\": \"Cursor released Cloud Agents with computer use capabilities - agents can now use the software they create to test changes and demo their work, producing merge-ready PRs with artifacts (videos, screenshots, and logs). Available on web, desktop, mobile, Slack, and GitHub. This represents a significant advancement in agentic capabilities.\",\n   155→    \"author\": \"Cursor Team\",\n   156→    \"source\": \"Product\",\n   157→    \"url\": \"https://cursor.com/changelog\",\n   158→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-26\",\n   159→    \"topics\": [\"AI coding\", \"Cursor\", \"computer use\", \"autonomous agents\", \"testing automation\"],\n   160→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   161→  },\n   162→  {\n   163→    \"title\": \"Claude Code v2.1.59: Auto-memory and /copy command\",\n   164→    \"description\": \"Claude Code v2.1.59 introduced auto-memory where Claude automatically saves useful context to auto-memory with /memory management, plus /copy command with interactive picker for code blocks. Community feedback was mixed: positive for solving cross-session memory pain points, but negative for performance issues and unwanted memory writing behavior.\",\n   165→    \"author\": \"Anthropic / Claude Code Team\",\n   166→    \"source\": \"Product\",\n   167→    \"url\": \"https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/releases/tag/v2.1.59\",\n   168→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-26\",\n   169→    \"topics\": [\"AI coding\", \"Claude Code\", \"memory management\", \"context management\", \"developer experience\"],\n   170→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   171→  }\n   172→]\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
      }
